etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in Journal of the Chemical Society. From octa- + decane, after German Octadecan

definitions: Any of the series of saturated hydrocarbons (alkanes) having the formula C₁₈ H₃₈; specifically (also "n-octadecane") the unbranched isomer CH₃ (CH₂)₁₆ CH₃.
